"Eigh" Names: Are They Really Growing in Popularity?
Tools: Python · pandas · seaborn · matplotlib
Data: SSA Baby Names — Social Security Card Applications, 1880–2022 · US Population (USAFacts)

Overview
Prompted by a Reddit observation that names containing "eigh" — Kayleigh, Ryleigh, Everleigh — seemed to be everywhere, this project investigates whether the trend is real, whether it's driven by population growth, and who's actually getting the names.
143 years of SSA baby name data. One very specific question.

Key Findings
Yes, "eigh" names are genuinely growing — not just a population effect.
Raw counts of eigh names rise sharply from the 1990s onward, but controlling for US population tells the same story. Per-100,000 people, eigh names have increased dramatically over the modern era, confirming the trend is real and not an artifact of there simply being more people.
Girls are getting almost all of them.
All-time counts broken down by sex show an overwhelming female skew. The "eigh" construction appears to function as a feminizing suffix in contemporary naming culture — attached to otherwise gender-neutral or male roots (Kyle → Kyleigh, Riley → Ryleigh, Ashley → Ashleigh).
Everleigh dominates the modern era.
The top "eigh" name by single-year count is Everleigh, a name that barely existed before the 2010s. Among all-time leaders: Everleigh, Ryleigh, Ashleigh, Leigh, Kayleigh, Kyleigh, Leighton, Haleigh, Charleigh.
The bottom of the list is something else entirely.
Least common eigh names include Journeigh, Kayleigha, Joeleigh, Coleigh, and Kaizleigh — names with counts so low they likely represent single families. Carry on my weighward son.
Methods

Parsed SSA annual name files (one .txt per year, 1880–2022) into a unified dataframe with year extracted from filename
Filtered for names containing the substring "eigh"
Aggregated counts by year to plot raw trend
Merged with US population data to calculate per-capita rate (eigh names per 100,000 people)
Grouped by sex for all-time gender breakdown
Identified top name per year via idxmax, and ranked all-time by total count

Data Sources

SSA Baby Names: https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/baby-names-from-social-security-card-applications-national-data
US Population: USAFacts historical population CSV
